<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-525-792  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 525 792.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer-Aided Engineering  May 1990 v9 n5 p72(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Europe's Silicon Valley. (includes related article about CAD/CAMin France)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Krouse, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>As Europe moves towards 1992 when economic and trade barriersbetween 12 European nations dissolve, Brussels is emerging as thecapital of this new European Community, Paris as the center ofbusiness and entertainment, and the area around Toulouse, France,their Silicon Valley.andP;  Toulouse, in the south of France, is thecountry's primary area for the development of industrial robotsand automation equipment and second only to Paris in universityenrollment.andP;  Toulouse employs 18,000 people in the aerospaceindustry, 8,000 in electronic parts production, 4,000 incomputers, and 3,000 in bio-research.andP;  US companies should takeadvantage of the growing number of technology-oriented trade showsheld in Europe, which permit US companies to demonstrate theirproducts and see what the local technology offers.andP;  One of themajor shows is SITEF (the French acronym for InternationalExhibition of Technology for the Future), held every two years inToulouse.andP;  Aerospatiale, an aircraft manufacturer, is one of thebiggest design and manufacturing employers in the Toulouse area.andO;Six kilometers south of Toulouse is Labege-Innopole, an industrialpark which offers shuttle transportation, hotel and shopping, daycare, an arts center, and a sports center.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Silicon ValleyTrade ShowsAerospace IndustryFranceRobotics Industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>